<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 4:9<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I266c3570630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Constitutional Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f53db682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:9.</label.designator><headtext>Right to counsel</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In accord with federal precedent, Georgia courts have held that a criminal suspect who asks for a lawyer during a custodial interrogation may not be subject to further questioning by law enforcement until an attorney has been made available or until the suspect reinitiates the conversation.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2cb8e707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] Generally, a criminal suspect waives his constitutional right to counsel when he volunteers statements after receiving <ital>Miranda</ital> warnings.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2cb8e717fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Despite being told by the arresting officer that <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“no lawyer can do you any good at this point,”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> the Georgia Supreme Court in <page no="110"/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1994120200" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d708327fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Gober v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2cb8e727fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] found that a suspect&apos;s statements were voluntarily given after a <ital>Miranda</ital> warning because the officer was merely stating his opinion which did not deprive the suspect of his right to counsel.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Similarly, a suspect who invoked the right to counsel waives it with respect to statements made after he initiates further discussion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2cb8e737fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1993180567" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d8b5e27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Hopkins v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2cbb5807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] the defendant invoked the right to counsel after receiving a <ital>Miranda</ital> warning upon his arrest. <eos/><bos/>Subsequently, he made incriminating statements to the officer driving the police car while en route to the police station. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Supreme Court held that these statements were admissible because defendant waived his right to counsel upon initiating further discussion with law enforcement.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1993214966" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d9a0427fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brockman v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2cbb5817fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] the Court opined that it did not matter that the defendant had said that he “might” want to talk to an attorney because he later initiated discussions with the arresting officers. <eos/><bos/>The <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1993214966" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6da8aa27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brockman</ital></cite.query> court clearly enunciated the rule to be applied in cases of waiver of right to counsel by stating that, even when a suspect makes an unequivocal request for counsel, which cuts off all police-initiated interrogation, he may be interrogated further if he (1) initiates further discussion with the police and (2) knowingly and intelligently waives his <ital>Miranda</ital> rights.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2cbb5827fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia Supreme Court revisited the issue of right to counsel in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="2039087111" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6dbc3227fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>State v. Philpot</ital></cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2cbdc907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] In this case, the trial court granted a defendant&apos;s motion to suppress his custodial statement, where the defendant told the officer three different times to call his girlfriend and ask for his attorney. <eos/><bos/>The officer continued asking questions, and the defendant proceeded to answer them. <eos/><bos/>The Court held that the defendant unambiguously asked for his attorney when he told the office three times to call his girlfriend for his attorney&apos;s phone number. <eos/><bos/>The Court further reasoned that because there was no break in the interrogation, the statement should be suppressed. <eos/><bos/>The Court differentiated this case from <page no="111"/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="2038895373" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6dcad827fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Cheley v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2cbdc917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>] where the defendant took a 30-minute smoke break, and then requested to continue speaking with investigators.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic2cb8e707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="2025640211" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d5f6c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Wheeler v. State, 289 Ga. 537, 713 S.E.2d 393 (2011)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1994135547" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="If6d5f6c57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Davis v. U.S., 512 U.S. 452, 114 S. Ct. 2350, 129 L. Ed. 2d 362 (1994)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cb8e717fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1986112488" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="If6d66bf27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Moran v. Burbine, 475 U.S. 412, 106 S. Ct. 1135, 89 L. Ed. 2d 410 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="110"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cb8e727fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1994120200" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d756527fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Gober v. State, 264 Ga. 226, 226, 443 S.E.2d 616 (1994)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cb8e737fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1993180567" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d7f2927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Hopkins v. State, 263 Ga. 354, 434 S.E.2d 459 (1993)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1990026106" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d7f2957fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Zubiadul v. State, 193 Ga. App. 235, 236–38, 387 S.E.2d 431 (1989)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>For a good discussion of waiver and request for counsel, see also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="2016428055" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d840b27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Darby, 284 Ga. 271, 663 S.E.2d 160 (2008)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cbb5807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1993180567" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d8dcf27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Hopkins v. State, 263 Ga. 354, 434 S.E.2d 459 (1993)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cbb5817fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1993214966" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6d9c7527fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Brockman v. State, 263 Ga. 637, 436 S.E.2d 316 (1993)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cbb5827fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="1993214966" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6dad8c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Brockman v. State, 263 Ga. 637, 436 S.E.2d 316 (1993)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="2004057939" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6db26e27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">McDougal v. State, 277 Ga. 493, 591 S.E.2d 788 (2004)</cite.query> (court found that defendant summoning police to his holding cell was not a waiver of previously invoked right to counsel).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cbdc907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="2039087111" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6dbea327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Philpot, 299 Ga. 206, 787 S.E.2d 181 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="111"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2cbdc917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018122" w-serial-number="2038895373" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If6dcd4927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Cheley v. State, 299 Ga. 88, 786 S.E.2d 642 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 4:9<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
